# Frontend Conventions

Follow AGENT.md; these are the essentials when editing frontend code.

## Structure

- **Pages**: `src/pages/` — one component per route; file name matches page (e.g. `DashboardPage.tsx`).
- **Components**: `src/components/` — shared UI; one component per file.
- **API**: `src/api/` — fetch wrappers and response types only; no business logic.
- **Layout / routing / theme**: `src/app/` — App shell, routes, theme tokens.
- **Styles**: `src/styles/` for global CSS; CSS Modules (`.module.css`) next to components.

## Components

- Functional components only.
- File name = component name (e.g. `HealthStatus.tsx` exports `HealthStatus`).
- Keep Pages, Components, and API layer clearly separated.

## Naming

- Components and files: PascalCase (`HealthStatus.tsx`, `Sidebar`).
- API functions and variables: camelCase (`fetchHealth()`).
- Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE or `as const`.
- CSS module classes: camelCase (`styles.root`, `styles.linkActive`).

## Accessibility & document outline

- One logical `<h1>` per route (the page title). App chrome (logo, sidebar, header) must not use `<h1>`.
- Use semantic HTML and ARIA where it helps (`nav`, `main`, `aria-label`, `role="status"` for dynamic content).

## State & API

- Prefer local component state; no global state library for MVP.
- Every API call must handle: loading, error, and empty states where applicable.

## Linting

- Run `npm run lint` in `frontend/` before commit. No ESLint errors. TypeScript strict; no `any`.
